\cf0 \cb1 Jason is a first quarter freshman at Stanford. He enjoys walking because he is able to effectively use his time to do other tasks like texting friends, or reading (above). However, he says that sometimes he is worried because he is so engrossed that bikes might hit him. Jason also told me that he enjoys walking because since it is his first quarter, he is able to see parts of Stanford that he has never seen before, and find things that he would have missed otherwise. For example, he saw a Stanford reunion event as we were walking along. However, I observed that these \'a0two enjoyable aspects of walking are mutually exclusive. If Jason was taking in his surroundings, he would not be able to multi-task. Similarly, if he was reading, he wouldn't have his head up and be able to take everything in. So, it would seem that an application should focus on enhancing only one of these aspects. Jason said the one drawback of walking is that he is sometimes late to class because it takes so long. He said he would like an application that would note when he woke up, when he left, and when he arrived at classes, which could learn about how long it took him to get places, so that it could tell him to leave in the future at the appropriate time for him to arrive on time.
