\f0\fs26 \cf0 \cb2 Kenny is a junior who started walking last year after his bike broke. He says it is one of the best things that has happened to him in his Stanford career. He walks very slowly both to and from class, and frequently stopped to talk to people along the way. He says that he particularly likes this aspect of walking, since he is able to engage more with people when walking because he has more time with them and doesn't have to focus on dodging things like when biking. Kenny said that this expanded focus applies to the rest of his surroundings. He says he notices much more when walking. For example, on our walk, Kenny noticed that the flowers were in bloom (above). Kenny also made efforts along our walk to try out new routes. He took detours through the library and through gardens. He said he likes this because he is going places bikes cannot go, and because he gets to experience things he would otherwise miss. He would like an application that would offer him alternative routes so that he can see new things. On our way back from class, Kenny commented that he was very early to class. He said that the biggest problem with walking is his inability to gauge time to walk places. For known places, he usually knows how long it will take, but when he is going somewhere for the first time, he will often over or underestimate how long it takes to get there. He also mentioned that there really is no good calculator for this, as google maps is pretty bad. He said that the worst example of this was when he was walking to the caltrain station, and google maps told him it would take 10 minutes to walk to the 2 miles there!\'a0
