Google Maps - Google maps has a great application where you can search for locations, see what they look like, and get directions to them. It also offers you alternative routes to get places if you add in waypoints. This could be useful to expand upon for walking, by developing a similar application with more accurate times of how long it takes to get places, that could offer routes on walking trails instead of roads.\
Sonar - This application shows who is around you at local places of interest. This could be more useful for walkers if you had a network of people on it that you knew were walkers, and then could see who was nearby you and your current class to find someone to walk and chat with. It could also be limited to a network of your friends so random people wouldn't creepily know where you were.\
WordPress - Wordpress is a fantastic way to blog about things you have done and places you have been. It would be cool to have a similar application that would chronicle what walks you have taken and share pictures, so that other people could see the routes.\
A Day's outing - This application shows things to do around you based on your location (GPS or zip code). It would be cool to have an application that would show you cool things around Stanford that you didn't already know about, when you are in the vicinity of them and can make a quick detour to check them out. It would also be cool to be able to drop pins when you discover cool Stanford spots like the attic of synergy, to let other Stanford students know there is something cool there to check out.\
\'a0Trip Advisor - This site reviews attractions in cities, and gives tourists options of what cool things they can do on vacation. It also has user reviews of the attractions, to give tourists a better idea of what kind of experience they are getting themselves into. It would be helpful to have reviews of what routes to take, so people could find new routes to try out, and which ones they should avoid.\
